==Chemistry==
Generally, peptide neurotoxins can be divided into two major families, the ‘long chain neurotoxins’ (LCN) with 60- to 70-residue range and known to contain eight [[cysteine]] residues; and the ‘short chain neurotoxins’ (SCN) with 30 to 40 peptides with six or eight cysteine residues. Birtoxin, together with other birtoxin-like peptides including [[bestoxin]], is 58 amino-acid residues long, close to the ‘long chain’ family but with six cysteine residues. Birtoxin is reticulated by three [[disulfide]] bridges, instead of four, compared to other LCNs
.<ref name="BBRC1">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.bbrc.2005.05.148 |title=New “Birtoxin analogs” from [[Androctonus australis]] venom |year=1999 |last1=Martin-Eauclaire |first1=M-F |last2=Cearda |first2=B. |last3=Bosmans |first3=F. |last4=Rossoa |first4=J-P. |last5=Tytgat |first5=J. |last6= Bougisa |first6=P.E. |journal=Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications |volume=333 |issue=2 |pages=524–530|pmid=15963953}}</ref> Therefore it is considered to be the evolutionary link between ‘long chain’- and ‘short chain’- families.<ref name="EJM2">{{cite journal |doi=10.1046/j.1432-1327.1999.00625.x |title=Scorpion toxins specific for Na+-channels |year=1999 |last1=Possani |first1=L.D. |last2=Becerrill |first2=B. |last3=Delepierre |first3=M. |last4=Tytgat Hammock |first4=J. |journal=European Journal of Biochemistry |volume=264 |pages=287–300|pmid=10491073}}</ref><ref name="Biochem1">{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/bi00203a010 |title=Primary and NMR three-dimensional structure determination of a novel crustacean toxin from the venom of the scorpion Centruroides limpidus limpidus Karsch |year=1994 |last1=Lebreton |first1=F. |last2=Delepierre |first2=M. |last3=Ramirez |first3=A.N. |last4=Balderas |first4=C. |last5=Possani |first5=L.D. |journal=Biochemistry |volume=33(37) |pages=11135–11149|pmid=7727365}}</ref><ref name="JCB1">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S1095-6433(98)10140-X |title=Purification and primary structure of low molecular mass peptides from scorpion (Buthus sindicus) venom |year=1994 |last1=Lebreton |first1=F. |last2=Delepierre |first2=M. |last3=Ramirez |first3=A.N. |last4=Balderas |first4=C. |last5=Possani |first5=L.D. |journal=Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology – Part A: Molecular & Integrative Physiology |volume=121 |issue=4 |pages=323–332}}</ref><ref name="TR1">{{cite journal |doi=10.3109/15569549809009247 |title= Functional anatomy of scorpion toxins affecting sodium channels |year=1998 |last1=Gordon |first1=D. |last2=Savarin |first2=P. |last3=Gurevitz |first3=M. |last4=Zinn-Justin |first4=S. |journal=[[Toxin Reviews]] |volume=17 |pages=131–159}}</ref>

==Mode of action==
Birtoxin affects the [[Sodium channel#Gating|gating mechanism of sodium channels]] by binding to neurotoxin receptor site 4 of the channel, resulting in the lowering of the voltage threshold of the channel and a reduction in the current amplitude. Due to the change in the activation the sodium channel will open at smaller depolarisations. This causes increased excitability, which leads to symptoms such as convulsions, continuous urination, tremors and tachypnea (faster breathing).<ref name="EJM1" /><ref name="Biochemie">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0300-9084(00)01174-3 |title=Molecular mechanisms of neurotoxin action on voltage-gated sodium channels |year=2000 |last1=Cestèle |first1=S. |last2=Catterall |first2=W.A. |journal=Biochimie |volume=82 |issue=9–10 |pages=883–892 |pmid=11086218}}</ref>

==Toxicity==
Birtoxin only affects mammals. No effect is found on reptiles, insects or fish. In experiments performed on mice, symptoms such as convulsions, continuous urination, tremors and [[tachypnea]] occurred 10 minutes after injection and increased during 30 minutes. An injection of 1 μg of birtoxin resulted in severe [[neurotoxic]] effects for 24 hours, but this dose is not lethal to mice. LD<sub>99</sub> in mice is achieved at 2 μg.<ref name="EJM1" />

An [[antibody]] against the N-terminus of the birtoxin protein structure has been shown to neutralize the venom of the South African spitting scorpion, and such antibodies may be useful clinically to treat [[envenomation]].<ref name="Inceoglu2006">{{cite journal
